========================================
1. OpenAI non-streaming — three identical big-prefix requests
========================================
Expectation:
  request 1 (miss)  = Cursor's real cached_tokens (~4675), header 'real'
  request 2/3 (hit) = simulator's ~13306 estimate, header 'simulated' or 'mixed'

-- Request 1 (fresh prefix)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: real
   usage: prompt_tokens=22961 completion_tokens=195 cached_tokens=4675

-- Request 2 (identical prefix)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: mixed
   usage: prompt_tokens=22961 completion_tokens=178 cached_tokens=13306

-- Request 3 (identical prefix)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: mixed
   usage: prompt_tokens=22961 completion_tokens=274 cached_tokens=13306

Observations:
  • cached_tokens progresses 4675 -> 13306 -> 13306, matching Anthropic-style
    monotonic behaviour on prefix reuse.
  • header transitions 'real' -> 'mixed' because Cursor's own cache_read is
    still non-zero (its internal system prompt cache is warm), so we emit
    'mixed' to signal "both simulator and Cursor cache_read contributed".

========================================
2. OpenAI non-streaming — different prefix
========================================
Expectation: fresh prefix -> miss -> pass through Cursor's numbers, header 'real'.

-- Request 4 (different prefix; poetry-expert system prompt)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: real
   usage: prompt_tokens=17487 completion_tokens=439 cached_tokens=13024

Note: cached_tokens=13024 is Cursor's raw number for this call (they warmed
up their internal cache for our account by this point in the session).
Simulator did NOT override — header is 'real' as expected. Distinct prefix
means a fresh entry was added to our store; a second call with this same
prefix would flip to 'simulated'/'mixed'.

========================================
3. OpenAI streaming — identical requests
========================================
Same big_payload but with stream=true and stream_options.include_usage=true.
Streaming responses commit the response header before body bytes, so the
header can only distinguish 'real' (miss) from 'simulated' (hit) — the
'mixed' label requires post-stream knowledge and is not used here.

-- Stream 1 (prefix already recorded in section 1)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: simulated
   usage: prompt_tokens=22961 cached_tokens=13306

-- Stream 2 (identical prefix, still a hit)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: simulated
   usage: prompt_tokens=22961 cached_tokens=13306

Both streaming turns emit cached_tokens=13306 (simulator), header 'simulated'.
Same behaviour as non-streaming, minus the 'mixed' discriminator.

========================================
4. Anthropic non-streaming — cache_creation lifecycle
========================================
Uses a similar big prefix in Anthropic's system+messages shape (system=<big
string>, one user, one assistant, then the fresh user turn). On miss we
advertise cache_creation_input_tokens = simulated so clients see the
Anthropic-shaped 'ephemeral' write lifecycle before the read hits.

-- Anthropic 1 (fresh prefix)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: real
   usage: {"cache_creation_input_tokens":6513, "cache_read_input_tokens":4675,
           "input_tokens":13692, "output_tokens":243}

-- Anthropic 2 (identical prefix)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: mixed
   usage: {"cache_creation_input_tokens":0, "cache_read_input_tokens":6513,
           "input_tokens":11854, "output_tokens":124}

Observations:
  • Request 1: our simulator estimated the prefix at 6513 tokens (the
    Anthropic payload has a smaller stable prefix than the OpenAI one).
    cache_creation_input_tokens = 6513 (simulated write).
    cache_read_input_tokens = 4675 (Cursor's real internal cache — pass-through).
  • Request 2: cache_creation goes to 0, cache_read jumps to the simulator's
    6513 (max(real=4675, simulated=6513) = 6513). Header 'mixed' because
    Cursor's real cache_read was > 0.

========================================
5. Disabled state (backward compat)
========================================
Restart with CURSOR_PROXY_SIMULATE_CACHE=false to confirm the simulator is
truly bypassed and callers doing research get Cursor's raw numbers.

$ CURSOR_PROXY_SIMULATE_CACHE=false /tmp/cursor-proxy-simcache -addr 127.0.0.1:18317
2026/07/10 04:20:21 [proxy] sim-cache disabled (real Cursor cache_read numbers pass through)
2026/07/10 04:20:21 [proxy] cursor account loaded: email=tinsels_boxy.5l@icloud.com
2026/07/10 04:20:21 [proxy] listening on http://127.0.0.1:18317

-- Request A (same big_payload; sim off so no override)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: real
   usage: prompt_tokens=22961 completion_tokens=120 cached_tokens=4675

-- Request B (identical to A; sim off so no override even though Cursor cache_read is warm)
   HTTP/1.1 200 OK
   X-Cursor-Cache-Source: real
   usage: prompt_tokens=22961 completion_tokens=107 cached_tokens=4675

cached_tokens stays at Cursor's raw 4675 across both calls, header 'real'.
No override — backward-compat preserved for research use.

========================================
Summary
========================================

| Test                          | cached_tokens | header      |
| ---                           | ---           | ---         |
| OpenAI req 1 (miss)           | 4675          | real        |
| OpenAI req 2 (hit)            | 13306         | mixed       |
| OpenAI req 3 (hit)            | 13306         | mixed       |
| OpenAI req 4 (different)      | 13024 (real)  | real        |
| OpenAI stream 1 (hit)         | 13306         | simulated   |
| OpenAI stream 2 (hit)         | 13306         | simulated   |
| Anthropic req 1 (miss)        | 4675  read    | real        |
|                               | 6513  create  |             |
| Anthropic req 2 (hit)         | 6513  read    | mixed       |
|                               | 0     create  |             |
| Disabled req A                | 4675          | real        |
| Disabled req B                | 4675          | real        |

Progression is monotonic and stable across identical prefixes; drops back
to real when the prefix changes; opts out cleanly when the simulator is
disabled. Dashboards (CPA, new-api) will see the Anthropic-style
prompt-cache semantics they expect.

